<s1 id=ToStartAudio>To Open or Start Audio
        <idx>Audio, using<sort>audio, using<\idx>
        <idx>starting Audio<sort>starting audio<\idx>
        <idx>opening Audio<sort>opening audio<\idx>
	<idx>icon:opening Audio <\idx> 
	<idx>Audio icon <\idx> 
	<idx>workspace programs menu <\idx> 
	<idx>front panel <\idx> 
	<idx>command line <\idx> 

<procedure>To Open Audio from an Icon
<p>If Audio has previously been open and the Audio icon is on
the desktop, double-click the icon to open Audio.

<newline>&empty;
<p gentity=Audio-Icon gposition=left>Audio Icon
<newline>&empty;

<newline>&empty;

<procedure>To Open Audio from the Workspace Programs Menu
<list order>
<item>Place the mouse pointer anywhere on the background of the desktop (the
workspace) and click mouse button 3. 
<p>The Workspace menu appears.
<item>Choose Programs and then choose Audio from the Programs submenu.
<p>The Audio main window appears.
<\list>

<newline>&empty;

<procedure>To Start Audio from the Front Panel
<p>If Audio has been installed in the Front Panel (either directly
in the Front Panel or in the Personal Applications subpanel), click the 
Audio icon to start the application.  

<p>To install Audio in the Front Panel, see
<link hyperlink="Appmanager CopyAppToFrontPanel">To Put an Application Icon
in the Front Panel<\link> in the Application Manager help volume for 
instructions.  Click Backtrack to return to this location after reading 
the instructions.


<procedure>To Start Audio from the Command Line
	<idx>command-line syntax<\idx>
	<idx>syntax, command-line<\idx>
	<idx>sdtaudio<\idx>
	<idx>starting Audio<sort>starting audio<\idx>

<p>You can start Audio and open audio files directly from the command line.

<list bullet>
<item> Type <computer>sdtaudio<\computer> to start Audio.

<item> Type <computer>sdtaudio<\computer> <emph>filename<\emph> to start Audio 
and open a specific audio file.
<\list>

<newline>&empty;

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToOpenFile>
<item> <xref ToRecord> 
<item> <xref ToExitAudio>
<\list>

<s1 id=ToSetStartOptions>To Specify Startup Options
	<idx>startup options <\idx> 
	<idx>Options:to specify<sort>options:to specify<\idx> 
	<idx>standard view <\idx> 
	<idx>waveform view <\idx> 

Audio can be started with or without the waveform display. 

<list order> 
<item> Choose Startup from the Options menu.
<p>The Audio Options dialog box, with Startup category selected, is
displayed. 

<newline>&empty;<newline>
<figure nonumber entity=Audio-Options-Startup
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<item> Click Standard View or Waveform View, as appropriate.

<item> Click OK to apply your choice and close the dialog box.
<p>The new startup view will display the next time you start Audio.
<\list> 

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref AudioOptionsDialogStartup> 
<item> <xref AudioWindow> 
<item> <xref AudioWindowWave> 
<item> <xref ToOpenFile>
<item> <xref ToPlayAudioFile>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToExitAudio>To Exit Audio
	<idx>exiting Audio<sort>exiting audio<\idx>
	<idx>quitting Audio<sort>quitting audio<\idx>
	<idx>closing Audio<sort>closing audio<\idx>
	<idx>Alt-F4 <\idx> 

<list bullet> 
<item> Choose Exit from the File menu or Close from the Window menu or
hold down the Alt key and press the F4 key with the mouse cursor over
the Audio main window to exit Audio. 
<\list>

If you have recorded an audio file and not saved it, you are asked if
you want to save it. Click Yes to save it; click No if you do
not want to save it; click Cancel to cancel the exit operation. 

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToSaveANewFile>
<\list>

<s1 id=ToOpenFile> To Open an Audio File
	<idx>open file <\idx>
	<idx>file:open <\idx> 
	<idx>Audio file:open<sort>audio file:open <\idx> 
	<idx>Control+O <sort>control+o <\idx> 
	<idx>Ctrl+O <sort>ctrl+o <\idx> 

<list order> 
<item> Choose Open from the File menu or hold down the Control key and
press "o" with the mouse cursor over the Audio main window.

<p>The Audio-Open File dialog box is displayed.

<newline>&empty;<newline>
<figure nonumber entity=Audio-Open-Dialog
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<item> Navigate to the folder where the audio file is located.
<p> Navigate by selecting a folder in the Folders list or by entering
a folder name in the Enter path or folder name text field. 
<item> Optional: Type an audio-file suffix (au, wav, aiff) after the
asterisk (*) in the Filter field.
<p> Only files with the specified suffix will be listed in the
Files field.
<item> Press Return or click Update to update the change in the folder
location or filter field.
<item> Select a file in the Files list.
<item> Double-click on the file in the list or select it and click OK.
<p> The selected file is opened. If Automatically play audio file
on Open is selected in the Options-Play dialog box, the audio
file starts playing.
<\list>

<procedure> See Also  
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToOpenFileDnd> 
<item> <xref AudioOpenDialog> 
<item> <xref ToSetPlayOptions> 
<item> <xref ToPlayAudioFile> 
<item> <xref ToRecord>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToOpenFileDnd> To Open an Audio File with Drag and Drop
	<idx>open file <\idx>
	<idx>file:open <\idx> 
	<idx>Audio file:open<sort>audio file:open <\idx> 
	<idx>drag and drop:open file <\idx> 

<list order> 
<item>Open File Manager and navigate to the folder where the audio
file is located.
<item>Drag the audio file icon from File Manager and drop it on the
Audio main window.  
<p> The selected file is opened. If Automatically play audio file
on Open is selected in the Options-Play dialog box, the audio
file starts playing.
<\list>

<procedure> See Also  
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToOpenFile> 
<item> <xref ToSetPlayOptions> 
<item> <xref ToPlayAudioFile> 
<item> <xref ToRecord>
<\list>

<s1 id=ToSetPlayOptions> To Specify Play Options
	<idx>Options:to specify<sort>options:to specify<\idx> 
	<idx>play options:to specify <\idx> 
	<idx>automatically play <\idx> 
	<idx>default play volume <\idx> 
	<idx>balance audio output <\idx> 
	<idx>Options dialog box<sort>options dialog box<\idx>

You can specify whether an audio file is automatically played when you
open it and set default play volume and audio output balance
in the Options dialog box.

<list order>
<item> Choose Play from the Options menu.

<p> The Options dialog box is displayed, with Play selected as
the Category. If the Options dialog box is already displayed, choose
Play from the Category menu.

<newline>&empty;
<figure nonumber entity=Audio-Options-Play>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<item> Click Automatically play audio file on Open to select or
deselect this option. 

<item> Move the Set Default Play Volume and Balance Audio Output
sliders to desired positions.

<p> Position the mouse pointer over the slider and press mouse button 1 as
you move the mouse to change slider positions.

<item> Click OK to apply the specified values and close the Options
dialog box.

<\list>

<procedure> See Also 
<list bullet tight> 
<item> <xref ToOpenFile> 
<item> <xref AudioOptionsDialogPlay> 
<item> <xref ToPlayAudioFile> 
<\list> 


<s1 id=ToPlayAudioFile> To Play an Audio File
	<idx>play audio file <\idx> 
	<idx>audio file, play <\idx> 

Once you have opened an audio file or created a recording, you can
play it from your desktop. You can play AU, WAV, or AIFF files. 

<list order>

<item> Click the Play Audio button.

<newline>&empty;<newline>
<figure nonumber entity=Audio-PlayAudioCallouts>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<p> The file is played from the beginning if it has just
been opened or if you have just created the recording. If you
click the Stop Playing button during play and then click Play Audio,
play begins at the previous stop point. 

<p> See <xref ToSetDeviceOptions> for instructions for specifying a
different output device.

<p>Note that the Play Audio button is a toggle: before play, it is
Play Audio; during play, it is Stop Playing. Note also that the Play
and Go to buttons are inactive when no audio file has been opened or
recorded. 

<item> To move the play pointer to the beginning of the file, click
the Go to Start button.

<item> To move the play pointer to the end of the file, click the Go
to End button.

<item> To move the play pointer to a position within the file:

<list bullet>
<item> If the waveform is not displayed, drag the slider with mouse button 1.

<item> If the waveform is displayed, click anywhere in the waveform
window.
<\list> 

<p> When you click Play Audio, play begins at the play pointer
position. 

<item> To display a waveform representation of the current audio file,
click the Show Wave Window button.

<p>Note that the Show Wave Window button is a toggle; when clicked, it
becomes the Hide Wave Window button.

<\list>

<procedure> See Also 
<list bullet tight> 
<item> <xref ToSetPlayOptions> 
<item> <xref AudioWindow> 
<item> <xref AudioOptionsDialogPlay> 
<item> <xref ToOpenFile> 
<item> <xref ToOpenFileDnd> 
<\list> 


<s1 id=ToSetRecordOptions> To Specify Record Options
	<idx>Options:to specify<sort>options:to specify<\idx> 
	<idx>recording options:to set <\idx> 
	<idx>Options dialog box<sort>options dialog box<\idx>
	<idx>audio quality <\idx> 
	<idx>audio format <\idx> 
	<idx>use selected recording options <\idx> 
	<idx>default recording options <\idx> 
	<idx>options:recording <\idx> 
	<idx>ask me <\idx> 
	<idx>default recording volume <\idx> 
	<idx>recording volume <\idx> 
	<idx>volume:recording <\idx> 
	<idx>balance audio input <\idx> 
	<idx>input balance <\idx> 
	<idx>OK button:Options dialog box<sort>ok button:options dialog box<\idx>

You can specify audio quality, audio format, record volume, and input
balance in the Options dialog box. You can also specify whether the
set values will automatically be used when recording or if you will
specify the values when you start recording. 

<list order> 

<item> Choose Record from the Options menu.

<p> The Options dialog box is displayed, with Record selected as
the Category. If the Options dialog box is already displayed, choose
Record from the Category menu.

<newline>&empty;
<figure nonumber entity=Audio-Options-Record>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<item> Choose Voice, CD, or DAT from the Audio Quality menu.
<p>Voice is the default. 

<item> Choose AU, WAV, or AIFF from the Audio Format menu.
<p>AU is the default. 

<item> Determine whether to use the selected recording options as the
default for new files.

<list bullet>
<item> To use the selected recording options as the default, click Use
selected recording options as default for new files.

<item> To specify recording options when you click Record Audio, click Ask me
when I start recording.
<\list> 

<item> Set default record volume and balance the audio input.

<p> Position the mouse pointer over the slider and press mouse button 1 as
you move the mouse to set Default Record Volume and Balance Audio Input
sliders to desired positions.

<item> Click OK to apply the specified values and close the Options
dialog box.

<\list>

<procedure> See Also 
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref AudioOptionsDialogRecord> 
<item> <xref ToRecord> 
<item> <xref AudioFileFormats> 
<\list>


<s1 id=ToRecord> To Create a Recording

	<idx>record <\idx> 
	<idx>recording options <\idx> 
	<idx>microphone <\idx> 
	<idx>line in <\idx> 
	<idx>CD<sort>cd <\idx> 
	<idx>Control+N <sort>control+n <\idx> 
	<idx>Ctrl+N <sort>ctrl+n <\idx> 

You can record Audio files from a microphone, line-in, or CD source.

<list order>

<item> Specify recording options. 

<p> See <xref ToSetRecordOptions> and <xref ToSetDeviceOptions> for
instructions.

<item> Choose New from the File menu or hold down the Control key and
press "n" with the mouse cursor over the Audio main window.

<p> If a previous recording has not been saved, you are asked if you
want to save it. 

<item> Prepare to record.

<p> Be sure that the selected input device is connected to your
computer and ready for transmission, and that the microphone or other
input device is on.

<item> Click Record Audio button and start recording.

<p> Speak, sing, or play into the microphone or start transmission of
audio from a line-in or CD source. Recording starts as soon as you click
Record Audio unless you have specified Ask me when I start recording
in the Options-Record dialog box. 


<item> When recording is complete, click the Stop Recording button. 

<item> Click Play Audio button to play what you have just recorded.

<\list>

<p>See <xref ToSaveANewFile> for instructions for saving the recording.

<note>The Record Audio button, which becomes the Stop Recording button
during recording, is inactive if a file is open; the button's function
is not displayed in the Current function area when it is inactive.
Similarly, the Play and Go to buttons are inactive when no file has
been opened or recorded. <\note>
<procedure> See Also 
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToSetRecordOptions>
<item> <xref AudioOptionsDialogRecord> 
<item> <xref ToSetDeviceOptions> 
<item> <xref ToPlayAudioFile> 
<item> <xref ToSaveANewFile> 
<item> <xref AudioFileFormats> 

<\list> 


<s1 id=ToSaveANewFile> To Save an Audio File or Recording
	<idx>file <\idx> 
	<idx>save file <\idx> 
	<idx>Save As <sort> save as <\idx> 
	<idx>format:save file in other format <\idx> 
	<idx>audio format:save file in other format <\idx> 
	<idx>save recorded file <\idx> 
	<idx>recording, to save <\idx> 
	<idx>Control+A <sort>control+a <\idx> 
	<idx>Ctrl+A <sort>ctrl+a <\idx> 

You can save an existing audio file or a new recording in AU, AIFF, or
WAV format.

<list order>
<item> Choose Save As from the File menu or hold down the Control key and
press "a" with the mouse cursor over the Audio main window.
<p>The Audio - Save As dialog box will be displayed.

<item> Specify the folder in which you want to save the file.

<p>Change to a different folder, if you wish. Press Return or
click Update to update the folder location. 

<item> Choose a format (AU, WAV, or AIFF) from the Audio Format menu.
<p>AU is the default format. 

<item> Type a name in the Enter file name field.

Audio files are usually named with <computer>.au<\computer>,
<computer>.wav<\computer>, or <computer>.aiff<\computer> suffixes for
easy identification. To overwrite an existing file, double-click on
the filename in the Files list. 

<item> Click OK to save the audio file or recording.

<\list> 

<procedure> See Also 
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref AudioSaveAsDialog> 
<item> <xref ToRecord> 
<item> <xref AudioFileFormats> 
<\list> 


<s1 id=ToSetDeviceOptions> To Specify Input and Output Device Options
	<idx>speaker <\idx> 
	<idx>headphone <\idx> 
	<idx>line out <\idx> 
	<idx>microphone <\idx> 
	<idx>line in <\idx> 
	<idx>CD<sort>cd <\idx> 
	<idx>input source<\idx> 
	<idx>output device<\idx> 
	<idx>Options:to specify<sort>options:to specify<\idx> 
	<idx>device options <\idx> 

You can specify output (play) and input (record) devices for playing
and recording.

<list order>
<item> Choose Devices from the Options menu.

<p> The Options dialog box is displayed, with Devices selected as
the Category. If the Options dialog box is already displayed, choose
Devices from the Category menu.

<newline>&empty;
<figure nonumber entity=Audio-Options-Devices>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<item> Select Speaker, Headphone, or Line Out as Output Sources.

<p> Note that you can select more than one output source.
Only devices that are installed on your computer are active.

<item> Select Microphone, Line In, or CD as the Input Source.

<p> Only devices that are installed on your computer are active.

<item> Click OK to apply the specified values and close the Options
dialog box.

<\list>

<procedure> See Also 
<list bullet tight> 
<item> <xref AudioOptionsDialogDevices> 
<item> <xref ToPlayAudioFile> 
<item> <xref ToRecord> 
<item> <xref ToSetRecordOptions> 
<\list> 

<s1 id=ToDisplayFileInfo> To Display Information about an Audio File
	<idx>file length <\idx> 
	<idx>length:file <\idx> 
	<idx>size:file <\idx> 
	<idx>number of channels <\idx> 
	<idx>channels:number <\idx> 
	<idx>sample rate <\idx> 
	<idx>rate:sample <\idx> 
	<idx>encoding <\idx> 
	<idx>Audio File Information dialog box<sort>audio file information dialog box<\idx>
	<idx>File Size:Audio File Information dialog box<sort>file size:audio file information dialog box<\idx>
	<idx>image information, displaying<\idx>
	<idx>file information, displaying<\idx>
	<idx>displaying, file information<\idx>

<p>To view file information, choose Get Info from the File menu.

<p>Audio provides the following information about the current file:

<list bullet tight>
<item>File name
<item>File size in kilobytes
<item>File length in seconds
<item>Number of channels
<item>Sample rate
<item>Encoding
<\list>


